Lot of time to think while cross training the last few days.  Has been a rough couple of months of training.  Injury in November and running through that to nationals.  Then having a terrible course and tearing myself up on that.  Followed by 20 days of doing nothing at all.  Gaining 20 pounds. Coming back and having the same ankle pain for the first two months back running. Running some subpar races and then about three days and one workout with out pain. Slipping on ice and straining my lower back and right back to where I started.  If there was ever a winter to be hurt and not be able to run at least this was it.  The sidewalks continue to be covered in ice, the footing everywhere is bad and the polar vortex continues to pound us with negative temperatures.  It could always be worse.
Test run.  Didn't go well.  Feels okay if I have my arms on the side rail to support my weight.  But putting full weight on it hurts still.  Maybe if I lose some weight it will be fine

Well I never write. But I am feeling inspired here. Lots of people blog and people must read it otherwise they are just wasting their time. Not sure what I will write. Maybe I don't cuz I know I can't be as witty or amusing as Nick Ross but running 100 miles a week I must have something interesting to say. I was thinking about it as I jogged back after what you could call a workout and feeling sick. Lets say that eating 3 brats right before running hard isn't the greatest idea, but I am a champ so I kept them down. As I was doing MP and 10k pace which are much slower now than they use to be I was thinking about where I am at. As my friends and teammates are doing workouts that are as fast as my two races I have run this year I decided I am in a funk. The only way to get out of a funk is to run out of it. So I headed to Dam to Dam last year I had no expectations and I head there again this year with the same. Hopefully this year can get turned around.

Well tried to race today. Should have known better after yesterday went terrible and the warm up was bad. But started. Ran 2:18 through the 800.  Felt like I was being stabbed in the hip with a knife.  Didn't feel like I was able to fully push off that leg. Went through 800 and ran 200 more but felt like I was only using one leg. Had no response.  Never dropped out of a race before. Shouldn't have started even but hate to let that mentality sink in. Not the person to drop out. Thought that I was hurting and the team didn't need me so I let that thought into my head. I am going to take time off and really get healthy.  Basically haven't been healthy since last year. Still ran 15:40 and 1:13 with a bum leg and without having great training. Need to relax and really get better if I want to make any difference this year. Also someone stole everyone's phones and wallets from their bags. You like to think that people at track meets are good people. Sucks to have people like that in the sport. Total BS.
